Connecticut State
--------------------------
<http://dep.state.ct.us/mosquito/index.asp> [edited
On 29 Aug 2000, the State identified 21 additional WNV positive birds
collected between August 17-23, from *Bethel (1 crow), *Bloomfield (1
crow), Cheshire (1 crow), Darien (1 crow), Fairfield (5 crows), *Groton (1
crow), Milford (1 crow), *Monroe (2 crows), *New Britain (2 Crows), New
Canaan (1 crow), Shelton (2 crows), Wallingford (1 crow), *Waterbury (1
crow), West Hartford (1 crow). A (*) indicates a new town.
On 30 Aug 2000, the state reported 22 crows positive for West Nile Virus.
Birds were collected between 13-20 Aug 2000, from Darien (7 crows),
Fairfield (12 crows), *Madison (1 crow), Milford (1 crow), *Newington (1
crow), *indicates a new town.
On 1 Sep 2000, the State announced 4 additional West Nile virus (WNV)
positive birds. The birds were collected from 21-25 Aug 2000. The birds
were collected from the following city and towns: Stamford (2 crows),
Fairfield (1 crow), and *South Windsor (1 crow). (* denotes a new town)
For the week of 29 Aug 2000, 16 605 mosquitoes have tested negative for WNV
and EEE from 69 sites statewide. One isolation of Highlands J virus was
reported; [this virus does not cause disease in humans and is not
considered a veterinary threat.
******
Massachusetts State
--------------------
<http://www.state.ma.us/dph/media/Pr0828.htm> [edited
The Massachusetts Department of Public Health announced today test results
for West Nile Virus Surveillance. Eighteen birds that died between 19-23
Aug 2000 were found to be infected with West Nile Virus (WNV). One group of
_Culex_ species mosquitoes collected on 20 Aug 2000 from the Jamaica Plain
area of Boston was found positive for WNV. Of the 18 birds, there were 16
American crows, 1 sparrow and 1 bluebird. The total number of WNV-infected
birds to date in Massachusetts is now 54. Six crows, 1 sparrow and 1
bluebird were found in Brookline, 2 crows in the Jamaica Plain section of
Boston, and 1 crow in each of the following cities or towns: Cambridge,
Framingham, Holliston, Medford, Middleborough, Peabody, Seekonk and
Waltham. The findings for Cambridge, Framingham, Medford, Peabody, Seekonk
and Waltham were the first WNV-infected birds found this year in those
locations. The total number of WNV-infected mosquito pools to date is 2,
one in Brookline and 1 in Jamaica Plain.
The total number of WNV birds by location to date is Brookline (21); Boston
(14) which includes 10 from Jamaica Plain, and 1 each from Brighton, West
Roxbury, Roxbury and the Fenway; 4 from Newton; 2 each from Holliston and
Middleborough, and 1 each from Arlington, Cambridge, Hopkinton, Framingham,
Medford, Peabody, Seekonk, South Hadley, Upton, Waltham and Wellesley.
*******
New Jersey State
----------------
<http://www.state.nj.us/health/news/p00901a.htm> [edited
To date, blood and/or spinal fluid samples from 19 residents have been or
are in the process of being tested for the presence of WNV. In addition to
the one positive result, tests for 5 individuals have been negative and the
other test results are pending. These individuals either had symptoms
and/or signs that met the established WNV testing criteria or exhibited
most of the symptoms and are from counties where dead crows with the virus
have been discovered.
To date, 496 birds (495 crows and a cockatiel) found in 10 counties have
tested positive for the presence of WNV. Positive birds have been found in
Bergen (122), Essex (63), Hudson (48), Mercer (1), Middlesex (114),
Monmouth (54), Morris (6), Passaic (36), Somerset (2) and Union (50)
Counties. A total of 1 077 crows have been accepted for testing this year.
A total of 5 mosquito pools collected in Bergen County have tested positive
for the presence of WNV. More than 1 400 mosquito pools from all 21
counties have been collected by the Rutgers Mosquito Research and Control
Unit and tested by the Department of Health and Senior Services and/or the CDC.
Blood samples taken weekly from sentinel chicken flocks placed in all 21
counties and tested by the New Jersey Department of Agriculture have all
been negative for the presence of WNV to date. And blood samples of 1 115
house sparrows collected in Bergen, Passaic and Sussex Counties and tested
by the CDC also did not detect WNV.
******
New York City
--------------------
<http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/doh/html/public/press00/pr87-901.html> [edited
Health Commissioner Neal L. Cohen, M.D., announced this afternoon that
evidence of West Nile virus (WNV) has been confirmed by the New York State
Department of Health in 11 additional birds collected in New York City, as
well as in one mosquito pool tested from mosquitoes trapped in Rodman's
Park, Bronx. This updates the New York City Department of Health (NYCDOH)
announcement this morning at a news conference at City Hall, that a seventh
New York City resident has tested positive for WNV. That individual, a 61
year-old man who lives in Woodrow, Staten Island, has been released from
the hospital and is at home recovering.
Five of the birds were collected from Manhattan (2 crows from Central Park
on 28 Aug 2000, one crow found in Gramercy Park 21 Aug 2000, one crow
collected from the Upper West Side 23 Aug 2000, and one captive bird which
died in East Harlem 17 Aug 2000). Two birds, both crows, were collected
from Queens (one found in Neponsit 22 Aug 2000, and one found in Cambria
Park 16 Aug 2000). Two additional crows were found in Brooklyn 21 Aug 2000,
in Bay Ridge and in East Flatbush. Another crow was found 21 Aug 2000 in
University Heights, Bronx. The eleventh bird, a gull, was found on Staten
Island 21 Aug 2000, in Fresh Kills.
******
New York State
----------------------
<http://www.health.state.ny.us/nysdoh/westnile/update/today.htm> [edited
On 29 Aug 2000 the New York State Health Department's Wadsworth Laboratory
reported 12 West Nile virus positive dead birds in the following counties:
Cayuga, 1; Dutchess, 1; Monroe, 1; New York City, 2 (Brooklyn, 1;
Manhattan, 1); Nassau, 2; Oneida, 1; Rensselaer, 1; Rockland, 1 and
Westchester, 2. The West Nile virus positive dead bird from Monroe County
is the first West Nile virus positive specimen in that county. The West
Nile virus positive mosquito pool with the unknown location from yesterday
was from Staten Island.
On 1 Sep 2000, The New York State Health Department's Wadsworth Laboratory
reported 46 West Nile virus positive dead birds in the following counties:
Cayuga, 1; Cattaraugus, 1; Chautauqua, 1; Chemung, 1; Clinton, 3; Columbia,
1; Cortland, 2; Dutchess, 1; Erie, 3; Essex, 2; Greene, 1; Madison, 2;
Monroe, 1; Nassau, 1; New York City, 11 (Brooklyn, 2; Bronx, 1; Manhattan,
5; Queens, 2; Staten Island, 1), Orange, 2; Oswego, 2; Rockland, 1;
Suffolk, 7 and Westchester, 2. Thirteen West Nile virus positive mosquito
pools were reported in the following counties: New York City, 1 (Bronx);
Rockland, 3; Suffolk, 9. The West Nile virus positive dead birds from
Cattaraugus County are the first West Nile virus positive specimens in that
county.
The total number of West Nile virus positive specimens for New York State
this year is 486 birds, 185 mosquito pools, 1 sentinel chicken, 6 live wild
birds, 3 bats, 1 horse and 7 human cases.
