[2
Date: 31 Aug 2000 14:35:04 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Associated Press, 31 Aug 2000 [edited

First confirmed West Nile virus-infected crow in New Hampshire
--------------------------------------------------------------
MANCHESTER: New Hampshire's first confirmed case of West Nile virus was
detected in a dead crow in Manchester, state and city officials announced
on Wednesday [30 Aug 2000. It is the first confirmation of the virus in
northern New England, although cases have cropped up in Massachusetts
[birds, horse and Connecticut [birds.
The crow was collected by the city's health officers 21 Aug 2000 and
submitted for testing at the state Department of Health and Human Services
Public Health Laboratories.
[West Nile virus likely exists in other parts of the state, said Jesse
Greenblatt, state epidemiologist with the state Department of Health and
Human Services' Office of Community and Public Health. The arrival of the
virus was only a matter of time and it could be here to stay, health
experts said during a news conference at Manchester City Hall to disclose
the findings. "West Nile virus is [both a short-term challenge and a
long-term challenge," Greenblatt said. "The virus will be present until
first frost here in northern New England, and then it may be here to stay
[if it is able to over-winter".
Additional birds are being collected and tested. Manchester and state
officials are continuing to trap and test mosquitoes for the virus, and are
considering spraying in at least a two-mile radius of where the dead crow
was located. Greenblatt said more than 40 birds have been collected
[already for testing. He said the presence of a single dead bird is not a
good measure of how the virus is affecting New Hampshire or the region. The
decision to spray for mosquito control is a local decision, town by town.
Greenblatt said no other towns in New Hampshire are now conducting spraying
specifically for the West Nile virus. There are only 9 mosquito spraying
programs in New Hampshire, most located in the Seacoast where wetlands and
marshes are widespread. While the Seacoast has one of the state's greatest
populations of mosquitoes due to the preponderance of wetlands, West Nile
virus is not associated with the quicker breeding saltmarsh mosquitoes. The
virus is documented in the mosquito species known as _Culex pipiens_, which
is more likely to be in urban and wet areas, such as catch basins.
The Department of Health and Human Services has a 7-day, 24-hour toll-free
West Nile virus informational hot line to help residents with concerns or
questions, or to report dead birds. The free number is (866) 273-6453.
[Byline: Dan Tuohy
