Date: 1 Sep 2000 11:13:07 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: 1 Sep 2000 [edited

West Nile Virus-infected bird found close to U.S.-Canadian border
-----------------------------------------------------------------
BROCKVILLE: Health officials in upper New York State have confirmed a case
of the deadly West Nile Virus in a dead bird found in St. Lawrence County,
about 45 kilometres south of the Canada-U.S. border. A dead bird found in
the town of Parishville, N.Y., tested positive for the virus, the St.
Lawrence County Public Health Department said yesterday in a press release.
The bird was brought to authorities for testing about 2 weeks ago.
Evidence [? of the virus that killed 7 people and sickened 62 more during
an outbreak last summer in New York City was found last month in Tonawanda,
N.Y., just east of Niagara Falls. Over the past month, residents in the
Niagara region have responded to the health unit's request that they be on
the lookout for dead crows, blue jays, ravens and other birds. More than 50
of the birds that were collected were shipped off to the University of
Guelph for testing, but none were infected with the virus. The health unit
said it would continue to pick up dead birds for testing until the mosquito
season ends in the fall. There is as yet no evidence that the virus has
crossed into Canada.
