[5
Date: 29 Aug 2000 11:11:28 -0500
From: Harvey Artsob <Harvey_Artsob@hc-sc.gc.ca>

West Nile Virus Surveillance in Canada: a comment
-------------------------------------------------
A recent posting on West Nile surveillance in Canada mentioned our dead
bird surveillance, but focused on our sentinel chicken program. It is
interesting to note that there has been a particular fascination by the
press about our sentinel chickens. We decided to use sentinel chickens due
to the fact that this system has been very successful in Canada for the
early detection of western equine encephalitis virus activity and due to
reports of West Nile virus antibodies in chickens in New York last year
following the outbreak. This program will be continued for the rest of the
year but will be seriously reevaluated at year's end.
I think it is important to stress that we have also been undertaking dead
bird surveillance since Jun [2000 which has proven to be a very effective
early warning system. The lead for this surveillance has been taken by the
Canadian Cooperative Wildlife Health Centre, a virtual centre comprised of
our 4 Canadian veterinary colleges in Saskatoon, Guelph, St Hyacinthe and
Charlottetown. Some additional testing is being done by selected provincial
veterinarians. This is not a casual undertaking waiting for the occasional
dead bird to be reported but has been widely publicized in order to solicit
public support in reporting dead birds. There are no guarantees that there
cannot be a human case or two in Canada without previous evidence in dead
birds but the current experience in the United States provides us some
reassurance that we are on the right track in our surveillance efforts.
--
Harvey Artsob
Chief, Zoonotic Diseases and Special Pathogens
National Microbiology Laboratory
Health Canada, Winnipeg
<Harvey_Artsob@hc-sc.gc.ca>
