[6
Date:Thu 31 Aug 2000 04:33:30 -0700
From: "Don Shroyer" <dshroyer@hotmail.com>

Sentinel chickens: some questions
---------------------------------
No substantive details are available about how sentinel chickens are being
used in the West Nile virus-active zone. Any surveillance method for a
mosquito-borne pathogen will fail if (1) it is inappropriate for the local
vector-pathogen cycle, (2) if it is inadequately implemented, or (3) if it
is applied to an inappropriate surveillance goal.
We deserve to be hearing more than unsubstantiated claims that "sentinels
are not working." Would anyone along the upper east coast USA care to
inform us (a) when sentinel chickens were first placed in field sites in
their area, (b) whether serum samples are obtained weekly, (c) whether
bleeding is by venipuncture or comb stick, (d) the specific serologic tests
performed, or (e) numbers of chickens or flocks deployed locally? Did
anyone have sentinels in the field in May or Jun [2000?
--
Donald A. Shroyer
Medical Entomologist
Indian River Mosquito Control District
Vero Beach, Florida
<dshroyer@hotmail.com>
